  "prompt": "Why do secants have a vertical asymptote?",
  "response": "The concept of vertical asymptotes is closely related to the behavior of functions as their inputs approach certain critical values. In the context of the secant function, the vertical asymptotes occur where the function is undefined, which happens when the denominator of the expression defining the secant is zero.\n\nTo understand why secants have vertical asymptotes, let's start by recalling the definition of the secant function in terms of the cosine function:\n\n\\[ \\sec(\\theta) = \\frac{1}{\\cos(\\theta)} \\]\n\nThe secant function is undefined whenever the cosine of the angle \\(\\theta\\) is zero because division by zero is undefined in mathematics. Therefore, the secant function will have vertical asymptotes at all angles \\(\\theta\\) where \\(\\cos(\\theta) = 0\\).\n\nNext, we need to identify the specific values of \\(\\theta\\) where the cosine function equals zero. Recall that the cosine function is zero at:\n\n\\[ \\theta = \\frac{\\pi}{2} + k\\pi \\quad \\text{for any integer } k \\]\n\nThis means that for any integer \\(k\\), the cosine of \\(\\theta\\) will be zero, and consequently, the secant function will be undefined at these points. As a result, the graph of the secant function will have vertical asymptotes at:\n\n\\[ \\theta = \\frac{\\pi}{2} + k\\pi \\]\n\nTo visualize this, consider the unit circle. The cosine of an angle in the unit circle corresponds to the x-coordinate of the point where the terminal side of the angle intersects the circle. When the cosine is zero, the point lies on the y-axis, meaning the angle is an odd multiple of \\(\\frac{\\pi}{2}\\).\n\nAt these angles, as \\(\\theta\\) approaches the values where \\(\\cos(\\theta) = 0\\), the secant function \\(\\sec(\\theta) = \\frac{1}{\\cos(\\theta)}\\) grows without bound in either the positive or negative direction. This unbounded growth is characteristic of vertical asymptotes, indicating that the function's value becomes infinitely large (either positive or negative) as it approaches these critical points.\n\n**Summary:**\n\nSecants have vertical asymptotes because the secant function is the reciprocal of the cosine function. The secant function is undefined and displays vertical asymptotes at all angles where the cosine is zero. Specifically, this occurs at:\n\n\\[ \\theta = \\frac{\\pi}{2} + k\\pi \\quad \\text{for any integer } k \\]\n\nAt these points, the denominator of the secant function becomes zero, leading to undefined values and the characteristic vertical asymptotes observed in its graph.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
